1
Argumentation-based approach to regulate in a more
responsible way,the urban transportation network
Aninda Maulik
Ecole des mines de Saint Etienne
Abstract
This report is built around the issues regarding urban transportation network, focusing on minimizing
road congestion and pollution level in the environment. An urban transportation network is organized
but the roads are congested. A lot of options are available for daily commute in urban transportation
system. We attempted to visualize a typical urban transportation system through a multi-agent simu-
lation. A microscopic simulator embedded in the Plateforme Territoire has been used to generate such
simulation. Platforme Territoire integrates a complex architecture which is involved in decision sup-
port. We can assume that a human brain uses an argumentation process to take a decision. Similarly,
we can make agents in the simulation of Platforme Territoire to make a decision, believe a new infor-
mation or explain a decision by combining argumentation with such a multi-agent simulation.Here in
this report, we will investigate how the agents in a multi-agent simulation can be programmed to take
the viable option using argumentation as a tool. In a multi-agent simulation for urban transportation
network, we have considered 5 alternatives such as bus,car,walk,bicycle and regulated area. These
alternatives exists between origin and destination points. One of the alternative namely regulated area
is actually a restricted area at the center of the city. We do not let agents cross this regulated area
under normal circumstances. During emergency situation or when an agent has an electric car, we
allow agents to cross this regulated area. In our experimental studies, we have simulated an urban
transportation network with and without regulated area. We have got very interesting results under
both the situation which have been discussed in details.
Keywords
multi-agent system; urban transportation network simulation; argumentation
1. Introduction
In a typical urban transportation network, serious road congestion exists due to high density
of travelers. Such road congestion due to trafﬁc leads to an intense air pollution. The in-
frastructure of urban transportation network in most of the developed nations in the world,
cannot be upgraded any further and hence it has become extremely important now more
than ever to have a sustainable transportation network. According to the latest trend, many
major cities around the world is restricting the access of cars into the centre of the city.
There are many advantages and disadvantages related to this current trend. Since the be-
ginning of times when the cars were introduced, the centre of the city’s pollution index has
always been above the threshold due to the amount of carbon emissions from fossil fuel
driven cars, which in turn has affected people’s health. Access to the city centres can be
made better, by allowing environmentally suitable transport options like bicycles. Public
transports like buses can still take people in and out of the city centre areas. Now, a multi-
agent simulation is a tool which would help us visualize such scenario and understand how
a typical urban traveler can be inﬂuenced to take the viable option using argumentation. For
special class of travelers with an electric car, we could allow them to cross the city centres,
thus appreciating choice of transport mode of a particular traveler. Several governments
2
such as French government is providing high incentives to switch to electric cars.Further
more, under exceptional circumstances like medical emergency situation, we can allow the
fossil fuel driven cars to cross the city centres.
Argumentation facilitates the agents to justify its choices in taking a responsible mode of
transportation which would synchronise societal objective such as keeping the pollution
index below the threshold and individual transportation preference. The remainder of this
report is structured as following sections. In Section 2, we present Platforme Territoire.
In section 3 we talk about different approach for regulating urban trafﬁc. In Section 4, we
analyse different works on a simulation based on argumentation. In Section 5, we propose
an argumentation-based model for the decision making of agents in a simulation. In Sec-
tion 6, we would discuss about some results. Finally, in Section 7 we conclude and give
some perspective for future works.
2. The Plateforme Territoire
Plateforme Territoire also has the ability to simulate a mobility situation. Platforme Terri-
toire integrates a complex architecture for territory governance regarding building, logis-
tics, mobility and environment. It is involved in decision support for the development of
sustainable urban logistics schemes, solving problem of moving people and is also involved
in responding to territorial issues with a strong environmental impact.
The microscopic simulator embedded in the Plateforme Territoire has been used to
make agents take decisions. Let’s consider a trip from one place to another. In this case,
Platforme Territoire has the ability to generate a simulation of different paths from the ori-
gin to the destination by considering different modes such as public transport, car, walking,
bicycle. The simulation can also generate different ways for different transportation modes
and argumentation can inﬂuence agents in avoiding a particular regulated area.
The below ﬁgure shows the car network which is marked in gray, the regulated car network
which is in blue. The other networks in the diagram are bus network which is marked in or-
ange. The green marked network is the walk only network and ﬁnally the red path is the bi-
cycle only network. The transport network for walking and bicycling is car+walk+bicycle.

3. Related work in urban transportation network
In an urban transportation network, there is a problem of high road congestion. Jeffrey and
Victor [3] attempts to solve this problem without seriously violating any individual user’s
preferred mode of transportation. To do that, the authors use a multi-agent system which is
formed by the co-operation of network managers, ISP(Internet Service Provider), travelers
equipped with road guidance system. The authors’ work is based on a group decision
process in which travelers has to negotiate in order to avail their choice of an alternative.
Our approach is based on individual agent decision making model. As a part of future
works, we would compare our model with a group decision making model like Jeffrey and
Victor.
We can proceed to a particular type of road network like highways where Praveen and
Dusan [4] tries to regulate trafﬁc situation. The way in which the authors try to solve this
problem is by addressing the travelers’ details. The travelers’ details that have been consid-
ered in here are origin and destination points. Like-wise, in our model, we have considered
travelers’ origin and destination points. Based on these two parameters, we have computed
what are the quickest, shortest, environmental friendly, less expensive alternatives for the
traveler’s origin and destination points.
A computer simulation in which the results were computed based on travelers’ origin and
destination points can be visualised in real-time by Kai et al. [5]. This is exactly what we
are also trying to do. In addition to this, we get results by the implementation of argumen-
tation.
According to the observations made by Christy et al. [6] user’s preference for a transport
mode is based on cause of its travel and the amount of travel time. These two parameters
4
could be inﬂuenced by addressing the psychology of the traveler. Similar to this, we tried
to classify the travelers based on their attitude towards a modal shift. For instance, we
classiﬁed the travelers into two class, one of which is travelers who are suitable for modal
shift to a more environmentally sustainable alternative. The second class of travelers on the
contrary are not suitable for modal shift. Further more, the travelers who are eligible for
modal shift have been considered for further classiﬁcation based on their mental state. Ex-
ample, if a traveler have a good educational background, then this traveler could be relied
upon for choosing an environmentally sustainable alternative.
The impact of this psychological tendencies that have been discussed just before should not
be misused for personal gains. The tendencies that have been used to inﬂuence the travelers
preference of an alternative should be in support of the environment according to Hans et.
al [7]. In their model, the authors visualise the impact of their idea over 1043 participants
from 6 urban areas of Norway. The authors were able to declare a success rate of 58 percent
because they found that 58 percent of the travelers did a modal shift to an environmentally
sustainable alternative which was not the personal norm, before the experiment. Such re-
sults are very interesting to us. We are expecting to get better results than 58 percent after
implementing argumentation over our multi-agent simulation.
Coming back to the implementation multi-agent co-operation, the model named CARA-
VAN(Congestion Avoidance and Route Allocation using Virtual Agent Negotiation) pro-
posed by Prajakta et al. [8] is based on vehicle allocations using Virtual Agent Negotiation
in the local vicinity. Vehicle agents communicate with each other before arriving at their
designated decision points (junctions) along the route. It has been proved to be better than
the classical shortest path algorithm by 21-43 percent and 13-17 percent in situation of traf-
ﬁc demand below network capacity and above network capacity respectively. The results
of the model seems very interesting but we are not dealing with co-operation or negotiation
within multi-agent simulation. Instead, we would like to evaluate the model CARAVAN
with individual agents and try to ﬁnd out if we get better results than the shortest path al-
gorithm.
Attempts which includes an introduction of tolls to regulate congestion in single and multi
link roads have been made by Andre et al. [9]. This approach is very interesting to us. This
could be thought of, as an incentive mechanism in order to inﬂuence the traveler to choose
a more environmental friendly alternative. Paying tolls for taking a car into the city could
inﬂuence the traveler to ditch their car and choose public transport instead. Right now, the
multi-agent simulation that we are experimenting with, is called Platforme Territoire. In
Platforme Territoire, we have an implementation of regulated area to restrict the number of
car within a city. Along with this regulated area, we could introduce tolls at the entry point
to the city thereby further decreasing the number of cars in the city limits.
Due to the popularity of the concept of using tolls to restrict the cars within city limits, it
was felt necessary to regulate the toll prices. Hence, Simoni et al. [10] has attempted to
come up with good toll pricing schemes.
Indeed the concept of introducing tolls have been proven successful, but with time lapse,
the number of cars goes on increasing. The good toll pricing schemes was able to control
the number of cars for sometime, though. The next step of regulating a highway have been
proposed by Peng et al. [11]. The authors propose to introduce auction-based highway
reservation system, just trying to keep a check over the number of cars that enters a city.
This work would be useful to us in the future. But, we understand the introduction of tolls
5
won’t be able to restrict the cars in the long run, so we would just introduce regulated area
near the centre of the city and observe the impact over vehicular congestion and total car-
bon content in the air.
Attempts to reduce the pollution index have been given by emphasizing on modal shift from
fossil fuel consuming vehicles to socially sustainable vehicles like electric cars. According
to Milos et al. [12] there could be negative impacts to switch to electric cars which could
be com-batted by developing efﬁcient trafﬁc control principles.
Now, question arises regarding extreme geographical location where trafﬁc control princi-
ples are almost negligent which is indeed a serious concern according to Aaron et al. [13] .
Pointing again to the class of travelers of the road, Nan et al. [14] says that there is an
existence of two main class which are rich and poor. Rich class travelers value time more
than the poor class and hence poor class has been targeted for modal shift by giving them
back a part of the toll amount. Based on the authors’ work, we have an idea of introducing
incentive mechanism based on argumentation in our future works.
After reviewing works on urban transportation network in point of view of multi agent
system we found that there is, to the best of our knowledge, no work exists that combines
argumentation and urban transportation network to make agents take better decision of
choosing the best alternative between their starting and destination points.
4. Simulation based on argumentation
There are several works which combines argumentation and multi-agent simulation, one
of which is given in [15] where they do a case study in assessing and comparing cultural
options available to farmers. In this work, the author has considered an argument as a
triplet comprising of option promoted by an argument, goal of an argument, justiﬁcation
for choosing that particular argument. Though we appreciate the details attached to an
argument but in practice, arguments are simple and need not be complicated. Moreover,
the implementation of their decision framework into simulation gives a partial view of the
problem, which is not our conclusion but the observation of the authors’.
Other works [16] also exists based on group decision making where agents are designed
with emotional properties, reason with incomplete information and use persuasive argu-
mentation to convince the other group elements about the best alternative choice. In this
regard, we have to note that in group decision making task, the choice of an alternative is
already settled. It is about information sharing, voting mechanism and negotiations that
come into action to explain the choice of an alternative. Thus the group decision making
model have not been our choice because of the fact that our agents have individual argu-
mentation graphs for themselves and they take decisions based on their graphs which is not
inﬂuenced by other agents’ graphs.
Finally, we would like to conclude this section by saying that there is no approach that
considers Amgoud and Prade model [17] to make agents take responsible decisions in a
multi-agent simulation for urban transportation network. The reason we choose this partic-
ular decision model is because of its simplicity. This simplistic decision making framework
is very expressive as well.

5. An argumentation-based model for the decision making of agents
in a simulation
Platforme Territoire is an environment in which we can visualise an urban transportation
network in form of a simulation. Thereafter, we can use argumentation to inﬂuence agent
to take a better responsible mode of transportation.
5.1. An implemented model for Plateforme Territoire
Platforme Territoire is a tool to generate behaviour of agents. In order to test our work,
we wanted a tool to check the behaviour of agents based on argumentation. But, what is
argumentation?
Argumentation is a process that leads an agent or a group of agents to make a decision,
believe a new information or explain a decision.
The next obvious question is, how do we generate arguments in an application like Plat-
forme Territoire?
There are two ways to generate arguments:
• the application owner can select its own arguments
• the application use indicators,which is the information available in the simulation,to
generate arguments
Now, we have an idea as to what is argumentation and how do we generate arguments. It’s
time for us to understand the mathematical model of an argumentation graph.
5.2. A formal argumentation system [1]
Now, that we have presented Platforme Territoire and have also mentioned that we will use
formal argumentation, so in this part, we are going to present the fundamental concepts of
argumentation framework.
Argumentation can be used to :
• determine what are the available alternatives to choose from
• decide which alternative to choose from the set of available alternatives
• form an opinion (i.e. a new belief) on a piece of information
• justify and explain its decision from a responsible point of view
Deﬁnition 5.1 (Argumentation framework ). We call an argumentation system a couple
hA, R i where :
A is a nonempty set of arguments.
R ⊆ A × A is a binary relation on A called attack relation
Following this, let’s try to understand the different argumentation semantics.

Deﬁnition 5.2 (Conﬂict-free). Let hA, R i be an argumentation system.
S ⊆ A is a conﬂict-free set of arguments iff A, B ∈ S s.t. A attacks B
Deﬁnition 5.3 (Defense and acceptability). Let hA, R i be an argumentation system. A set
of arguments S ⊆ A defends A ∈ A iff ∀B ∈ A if B attacks A, then ∃C ∈ S , C attacks B
An argument A ∈ A is acceptable with respect to S ⊆ A iff S defends A
Deﬁnition 5.4 (Admissibility). Let hA, R i be an argumentation system. S ⊆ A is admissible
if, and only if,
• S is conﬂict-free
• ∀A ∈ S , A is acceptable with respect to S
Deﬁnition 5.5 (Complete extensions). Let hA, R i be an argumentation system.
S ⊆ A is a complete extension if, and only if,
1. S is admissible i.e.
• A, B ∈ S s.t. A attacks B (conﬂict-free)
• ∀A ∈ S , ∀B ∈ A s.t. B attacks A , ∃C ∈ S , C attacks B (all arguments are accept-
able with respect to S )
2. S contains all arguments it defends i.e.

Meaning of this semantics
• All the arguments that are defended by S belong to S

• A, B ∈ S s.t. A attacks B (conﬂict-free)
• ∀A ∈ S , ∀B ∈ A s.t. B attacks A , ∃C ∈ S , C attacks B (all arguments are accept-

5.3. Arguments and attacks of argumentation graph
In Platforme Territoire, we have different alternatives such as bicycle network, walk net-
work, car network, regulated car network and public transport network.We would generate
arguments based on those alternatives. We started deﬁning the arguments based on the indi-
cators associated to these alternatives. To note, indicators are just the information available
for these alternatives. Some of the information that we are able to extract from Platforme
Territoire are as follows.
• distances to be traversed from point A to B by different alternatives
• duration to traverse a path between point A to B by different alternatives
• ﬁnancial cost involved to traverse a path between point A to B by different alterna-
tives
• environmental and noise costs involved to traverse a path between point A to B by
different alternatives
Now, let’s choose an alternative - say bicycle. Choosing an alternative such as bicycle
has some pros and cons. We can imagine that the pros of choosing a bicycle could be
in sync with the environmental sustainability. Thus we can have an argument such as
environmentalFriendlyTravelArgument. But there are many cons of choosing a bicycle
alternative such as availing this option during an emergency situation could mean that we
are choosing an alternative which is not the quickest. An argument associated to such an
alternative could be notTheQuickestTravelArgument.
Let’s try to now understand, how do we generate attacks. Again, considering an emer-
gency situation, we can generate an argument based on this situation, such as emergen-
cyArgument, which would attack the pro argument namely environmentalFriendlyTrave-
lArgument of the bicycle network. So, we have one attack from emergencyArgument to
environmentalFriendlyTravelArgument. Now, what is the result of this. The result of this,
is supposed to be a decision that an agent would take under emergency situation. The next
question is that, how do we arrive at a decision and what is a decision? A decision in this
case would be to choose an alternative which would be the quickest option. Thus, we can
have an argument namely quickestTravelArgument. This argument is based on the infor-
mation that we receive from Platforme Territoire. This information is dynamic meaning
that the quickest travel alternative would be different for different set of origin and desti-
nation points. Finally, an agent would choose the quickest alternative during an emergency
situation. A detailed description of the framework involved to use arguments and attacks
to arrive at a decision, could be explained in the next subsection

5.5. How to enumerate all preferred extensions?
Formal notations
• Let hA, R i be an argumentation system
• µ : A → {IN, OUT, BLANK, MUST _OUT, UNDEC}
(µ is a HashMap that associates for each argument if it belongs to the preferred
extension which is currently computed. )
Steps for the main program
1. Initially, associate all nodes to BLANK (i.e. µ ← {(x, BLANK) : x ∈ A})
2. Deﬁne a global variable PEXT that contains all preferred extensions
3. Call the recursive procedure ﬁnd-preferred-extensions(µ)
4. Returns the result of PEXT
Formal notations
• ∀x ∈ A, {x}
+
= {y ∈ A : (x, y) ∈ R } (i.e. arguments that are attacked by x)
• ∀x ∈ A, {x}
−
= {y ∈ A : (y, x) ∈ R } (i.e. arguments that attack x)
Steps for the procedure ﬁnd-preferred-extensions(µ)
1. If Termination condition is true i.e.
10
• all arguments x ∈ A are not BLANK (i.e. were treated)
• and there is no argument that must out then
⇒ we compute the preferred extension S ← {y ∈ A : µ(y) = IN} and add it to PEXT if S is not
already included in another preferred extension.
2. Else select any x ∈ A which is BLANK and call the recursive procedure for the case
where x is associated with the label IN (call IN-TRANS(x)), and the case where x is
UNDEC (call UNDEC-TRANS(x)).

argument is in favour of and what are the alternatives it is not in favour of.

at all times.

work.

Moving on, we have to understand that all the arguments cannot come into action at any
given point of time. For instance, the argument hasNoCarArgument would come into action
only when the user doesn’t have a car. As mentioned above, the fact that user doesn’t have
a car is 10 percent of the times. In this way, we have taken into account 4 speciﬁc situations
as follows:
• user has no car which is 10 percent of the times
– under this condition, hasNoCarArgument comes into action and for all other
condition hasNoCarArgument would not be considered
• It has been considered that 90 percent of the time, at-least one user has an electric
car
– under this condition, crossedARegulatedAreaArgument comes into action
• user has an emergency which is again 10 percent of the times
– under this condition, emergencyArgument comes into action and for all other
condition emergencyArgument would not be considered
• there exists a health crisis like corona pandemic.
– under this condition, crisisHealthArgument comes into action and for all other
condition crisisHealthArgument would not be considered
Thereafter, arguments such as walkingIsMakingYouSomeSportArgument, quickestTrav-
elArgument, environmentalFriendlyTravelArgument, shortestTravelArgument and expen-
siveTravelArgument has been taken into account. It is evident that these arguments would
always be considered while generating a viable option for an agent under all circumstances.
It is now time to deﬁne the attack relations of the arguments. A signiﬁcant amount of
imagination and utilisation of existing real life scenario led to successful generation of the
necessary attack relations.
The circumstances that have been accounted through four speciﬁc situations explained
above cannot exist as independently. Each situation has to co-exist in sync with another
situation.

attack relation would come into existence as described below.

7. Conclusion and perspective
It can be inferred from our research and derivations that the argumentation method can be
used efﬁciently and effectively to suggest or inﬂuence the individuals or agents to choose
the most viable and environmentally friendly mode of transportation. In today’s time when
the city centers globally have reached a saturation and peak in congestion, Platforme terri-
toire has created a solution to limit the congestion in the city centers and help in improving
the environment.
We started considering all the arguments for a typical urban transportation network. Then,
we associated each arguments to the pros and cons of each alternatives available in Plat-
forme Territoire. Thereafter, we tried to ﬁnd out what is the quickest, slowest, shortest,
longest, inexpensive, expensive, environmental friendly and environmental enemy alterna-
tives. Following this, we considered some situation like, if the user has no car, if the user
has an electric car, if there is an emergency or if there is a health crisis situation like corona
pandemic. Of-course all these situation have not been considered at once. Instead, we let
Platforme Territoire choose a situation and merge it with another situation. After this, we
generated attack relations. Finally, we considered the arguments based on situation. We
have also considered the arguments which are true for any situation along with the attack
22
relations and enumerated all preferred extension to take one decision for one agent. We did
experiments mainly on two situation, one of which is considering a regulated network and
other one is without regulated network.
We found that under normal condition, only one agent with a fossil fuel driven car chooses
to take the regulated network. This action is not a responsible action. In real life as well,
not every action is responsible. 5 agents choose the car network. 1 agent choose the bus
network. 6 agents choose the walk network. Please note that more than one agent would
have chosen the regulated network if they had an electric car. Again, the number of users
crossing the regulated area would have increased in an emergency situation.
Under no regulated area, we found that during health crisis situation like a corona pan-
demic, only two agents take the bus, which is the most unsafe option during a pandemic. 5
agents decide to take the walk network, which is moderately safe option during a pandemic.
Equal number of agents chooses car which is the safest option.It is understandable that in
these exceptional times, the pollution index will be low. People will tend to stay at home
which will result in low congestion and reduced level of pollution. Hence, under these
situations we can accommodate the agents choosing car as a viable mode of transportation
given the reason that the agents are choosing car as a viable option because of sanitation
concerns and maintaining a private space around them.
As a part of future work, we would consider a more realistic argumentation graph based on
statistical data. Further more, we would like to introduce the concept of tolls as a part
of our future work.Finally, argumentation combined with incentive mechanisms within
a game theory framework would be very interesting to work with. This argumentation
method can be implemented in different domains and ﬁelds of work. Interestingly, this
can be applied in the ﬁeld of law to analyse or derive conclusions based on a heavy set
of data or information like case-laws, regulations, policies. As a matter of fact while im-
plementing this Urban Transportation system in real-time, the viable options suggested by
Platform Territoire have to be in adherence to the local laws regarding transportation. Here,
an argumentation method can be used to generate valid arguments after processing all the
legal data put into the system to suggest an option which will also be legally acceptable
along with being environment friendly, cost effective or any other option as discussed in
the report.
